ce:section.ce:para:
Sensitivity is yet another significant aspect in order to define LPCDs as a fluorescent sensor. To assess the sensitivity of LPCDs, the emission spectral measurements were carried out by adding various concentrations of Fe3+ (0.5–180 μM) to 1 mL LPCDs solution separately (Fig. 4
                        a). Noticeably, the emission intensity of LPCDs (I0/I) at 468 nm reduced with the increasing concentration of Fe3+ because of the binding of Fe3+ on the surface of LPCDs. This phenomenon may be explained by the formation of LPCDs- Fe3+ ion complex with the active surface functional groups, which results the fluorescence quenching of LPCDs by Fe3+ ion. After that the response of LPCDs-Fe3+ system was investigated upon the addition of various amounts of PC (0.1–40 μM) (Fig. 4b). It was clearly noticed that the quenched fluorescence intensity of LPCDs was progressively restored with increasing concentration of PC. Based on these, two independent calibration graphs were constructed the ratios at I0/I (I refers the intensity of LPCDs with Fe3+ and I0 refers the intensity of LPCDs without Fe3+) and I/I0 (I refers the intensity of LPCDs-Fe3+ ion system and I0 refers the intensity of LPCDs with PC) verses Fe3+ ion (0.5–40 µM) and PC (0.1–40 µM) (Fig. S12 of Supporting Information). Both the calibration graphs exhibited good linearities (y = 0.0073x + 1.1121 for Fe3+ ion and y = 0.0069x + 0.548 for PC) with correlation coefficients (R2
                        ) of 0.9910 and 0.9926 for Fe3+ ion and PC, respectively. The limits of detections (LODs) 0.18 and 0.054 μM for Fe3+ ion and PC, respectively, which was calculated based on 3σ/s (σ referred as standard deviation of LPCDs and s is slope of calibration curve). The performance of LPCDs-based fluorescence method was compared with the reported fluorescence strategies (Cao et al., 2018; Zhu & Yan, 2018; Song et al., 2017; Shangguan et al., 2017; Pang & Liu, 2020; Tümay et al., 2020; Zhang et al., 2022; Atchudan et al., 2018; Atchudan et al., 2017) for the detection of Fe3+ ion (Table 1
                        ), confirming that the present method exhibited superior sensitivity as compared to other fluorescence methods in the literature. Furthermore, the analytical performance of the present method was also compared with other reported conventional analytical methods (Chen et al., 2022; Wu et al., 2018; Tang et al., 2022; Battaglin et al., 2011) for the detection of PC (Table 2
                        ), revealing that LPCDs acted as a simple fluorescent probe for the detection of PC with higher selectivity and sensitivity.
